🔐 What is Cloud Security?

Cloud security is the practice of protecting cloud-based systems, applications, and data from unauthorized access, cyberattacks, misconfigurations, and other security threats.

Why Cloud Security Matters

- Protects sensitive information.
- Prevents unauthorized access.
- Reduces the risk of data breaches.
- Helps organizations maintain secure and reliable cloud environments.

«One configuration mistake can expose thousands of sensitive records.»

---

🔵 The CIA Triad

The CIA Triad is one of the fundamental principles of information security.

Principle| Meaning| Question
Confidentiality| Only authorized users can access data.| Who can see the data?
Integrity| Data remains accurate and unaltered.| Has the data been changed correctly?
Availability| Systems and data remain accessible when needed.| Can authorized users access the data?

---

🤝 Shared Responsibility Model

Cloud security responsibilities are shared between the cloud provider and the customer.

Security of the Cloud (Cloud Provider)

The provider is responsible for securing:

- Physical data centers
- Servers
- Networking infrastructure
- Storage hardware

---

Security in the Cloud (Customer)

The customer is responsible for securing:

- Data
- IAM users and permissions
- Passwords
- Security configurations
- Applications

Both parties have different responsibilities, which is why it is called the Shared Responsibility Model.

---

👤 Identity and Access Management (IAM)

What is IAM?

Identity and Access Management (IAM) controls who can access cloud resources and what actions they are allowed to perform.

Why IAM is Important

Without IAM| With IAM
Anyone can access resources.| Access is restricted to authorized users.
High risk of unauthorized access.| Permissions are controlled.
Poor security.| Stronger protection of cloud resources.

IAM follows the Principle of Least Privilege, meaning users receive only the permissions required to perform their tasks.

Two Core Functions of IAM

1. Authentication verifies who a user is.
2. Authorization determines what the user is allowed to do.

